'''Daniel Sedin''' (born September 26, 1980) is a Swedish professional [[ice hockey]] [[winger (ice hockey)|winger]] with the [[Vancouver Canucks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), and serves as an alternate captain for the Canucks during [[home (sports)|home games]]. His identical twin brother [[Henrik Sedin|Henrik]] also plays for the Canucks, and is the team captain. Born and raised in [[Örnsköldsvik]], Sweden, they have played together throughout their careers; the pair are known for their effectiveness playing off one another.&lt;ref name=surprise/&gt; Daniel is known as a goal-scorer, while Henrik is known as a playmaker.&lt;ref name=&quot;have hart&quot;&gt;{{cite news|title=Does Sedin have Hart?|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/hockey/2010/04/06/13487241.html|accessdate=2010-04-19|date=2010-04-19|publisher=''[[Toronto Sun]]''|author=Dan DiSciullo}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Daniel began his professional career in the [[Elitserien|Swedish Elite League]] with [[Modo Hockey]] in 1997 and was co-recipient, with Henrik, of the 1999 [[Guldpucken|Golden Puck]] as Swedish player of the year. He played four seasons with Modo (including a return in 2004–05 due to the [[2004–05 NHL lockout|NHL lockout]]), helping the club to two consecutive appearances in the [[Le Mat Trophy]] Finals, in 1999 and 2000, where they lost both times. Selected second overall by the Canucks in the [[1999 NHL Entry Draft]], Daniel moved to the NHL in the [[2000–01 NHL season|2000–01 season]]. He has spent his entire NHL career in Vancouver; after emerging as a top player in the club during the [[2005–06 NHL season|2005–06 season]], he has since recorded six consecutive campaigns of at least 20 goals and 70 points.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; In [[2010–11 NHL season|2011]], he won the [[Art Ross Trophy]] as the league's leading point-scorer and the [[Ted Lindsay Award]] as the best player in the league, as voted by fellow players. Daniel was also nominated for the [[Hart Memorial Trophy]] as the league's [[most valuable player]]. In Sweden, he and Henrik were awarded the [[Victoria Stipendium]] as the country's athletes of the year.

Internationally, Daniel has competed for the [[Sweden men's national ice hockey team|Swedish national team]]. In addition to being a two-time [[Ice hockey at the Winter Olympics|Winter Olympian]], he has appeared in two European Junior Championships, two [[World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior Championships]] and four [[World Ice Hockey Championships|World Championships]]. He won a gold medal at the [[Ice hockey at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]], and bronze medals at the [[1999 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1999]] and [[2001 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2001 World Championships]].

==Early life==
Daniel was born on September 26, 1980, in [[Örnsköldsvik]], Sweden, six minutes after his identical twin brother, [[Henrik Sedin|Henrik]].&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt; The pair have two older brothers, Stefan and Peter.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt; Their father, Tommy, is a school vice principal and also played for [[Modo Hockey]] in the 1960s, while his mother, Tora, is a nurse.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt;  Daniel began playing organized hockey with Henrik when they were eight.&lt;ref name=tiger&gt;{{cite news|title=Sedins debate pucks, bad habits, Mrs. Tiger Woods|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/story?columnist=amber_david&amp;id=2679145|accessdate=2010-03-11|date=2006-12-01|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=David Amber}}&lt;/ref&gt; They did not regularly play on the same [[line (ice hockey)|line]] until Daniel switched from centre to wing at 14 years old.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt;  Daniel and Henrik both attended high school at the Nolaskolan Gymnasium in Sweden while playing professionally for Modo Hockey.&lt;ref name=mirror&gt;{{cite news|title=Mirror, mirror|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1014834/index.htm|accessdate=2010-03-11|date=1998-12-21|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''|author=Michael Farber}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Playing career==
===Modo Hockey (1997–2000)===
Aged 16, Daniel and Henrik began their professional careers in 1997–98 with Modo Hockey of the [[Elitserien|Swedish Elite League]]. Daniel recorded 12 points over 45 games during his rookie season. In his second professional year, he led Modo in scoring with 42 points in 50 games,&lt;ref name=modo99&gt;{{Cite web|title=1998–99 Modo Hockey Ornskoldsvik [SEL]|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0014321999.html|accessdate=2009-09-04|publisher=Hockeydb.com}}&lt;/ref&gt; helping the club to its second regular season title in team history.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Seriesegrare i Elitserien|url=http://www.hockeyligan.se/index.php?menu=1&amp;submenu=1&amp;subsubmenu=8|accessdate=2010-06-01|publisher=[[Swedish Elite League]]|language=Swedish}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel then added 12 points in 13 playoff games&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; as Modo advanced to the [[Le Mat Trophy]] Finals, where they lost to [[Brynäs IF]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Historik|url=http://www.modohockey.se/historik.cfm|accessdate=2010-06-01|publisher=[[Modo Hockey]]|language=Swedish}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; At the end of the campaign, Daniel and Henrik were named co-recipients of the [[Guldpucken|Golden Puck]], the Swedish player of the year award.&lt;ref name=legends&gt;{{cite web|title=Daniel Sedin|url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=19287|accessdate=2010-04-21|publisher=[[Hockey Hall of Fame]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The Sedins were considered top prospects for the [[1999 NHL Entry Draft]]. Rated as the top draft-eligible players from Europe,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=Sedin twins' dynamic changed draft|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/hockey/nhl/1999/draft/news/1999/06/26/nhldraft_twins/|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=1999-06-26|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; they were expected to be top five selections and expressed a desire to play for the same team.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt; As they were unlikely to be picked by the same team, their agent, [[Mike Barnett (ice hockey)|Mike Barnett]], president of international talent agency [[IMG (business)|IMG]], presented them with two options to circumvent the usual NHL draft process, allowing them to play together.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt; The first option was for the pair to enter the 1999 draft and not sign with their respective NHL clubs for two years, allowing them to become [[unrestricted free agent]]s. This option required that they play [[junior ice hockey|junior hockey]] in North America, which was not their intention.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt; Barnett also suggested either Henrik or Daniel opt out of the 1999 draft, hoping that the team that selected the first twin would select the other the following year.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt;  On the possibility of the Sedins' playing for separate teams, [[Vancouver Canucks]] scout [[Thomas Gradin]] commented, &quot;They're good enough to play with anyone, but separately their capacity might decrease by 10 or 15 percent.&quot;&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt; Nevertheless, Henrik and Daniel both entered the 1999 draft expecting to be selected by separate teams.&lt;ref name=tiger/&gt;  However, through a series of transactions,{{#tag:ref|The Canucks already possessed the 3rd overall pick in the [[1999 NHL Entry Draft]] that was used to select [[Henrik Sedin]]. They then acquired the 2nd overall pick to select Daniel as follows.
#The Canucks traded [[Bryan McCabe]] and their first-round pick in [[2000 NHL Entry Draft|2000]] or [[2001 NHL Entry Draft|2001]] to the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in exchange for the Blackhawks' first round pick (4th overall).
#The 4th overall pick acquired from the Blackhawks was then traded along with two third-round picks in the 1999 draft (75th and 88th) to the [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] in exchange for the Lightning's first-round pick (1st overall).
#The 1st overall pick acquired from the Lightning, along with a conditional third-round pick in the 2000 draft, was then traded to the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] for the Thrashers' first-round pick (2nd overall) under the condition that then-Thrashers GM [[Don Waddell]] not select either Sedin with the first overall pick.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Sedin twins' dynamics changed draft|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/hockey/nhl/1999/draft/news/1999/06/26/nhldraft_twins/|accessdate=2010-08-22|date=1999-06-26|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''|author=Associated Press}}&lt;/ref&gt;|group=notes}} Canucks general manager [[Brian Burke (ice hockey)|Brian Burke]] obtained the second and third overall picks, which he used to select Daniel and Henrik, respectively. Gradin notified them of the Canucks' intentions five minutes before the draft.&lt;ref name=tiger/&gt; Although [[Tampa Bay Lightning]] general manager [[Rick Dudley]] was ready to make Daniel his first overall choice before opening negotiations, he was convinced by Burke and Barnett that Daniel would not sign unless his brother was on the same team.&lt;ref name=surprise/&gt;

On July 27, 1999, a month following the draft, Daniel and Henrik signed three-year contracts with the Canucks.&lt;ref name=contract99/&gt; As the contract did not require them to begin playing in Vancouver immediately, they announced on August 12 they would return to Sweden to play one more season with Modo.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Around the world|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/awrld131.shtml|accessdate=2010-05-25|date=1999-08-13|publisher=''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]''|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=February 2012|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; During the 1999–2000 season, Daniel finished second in team scoring with 45 points in 50 games, two points behind Henrik.&lt;ref name=modo00&gt;{{Cite web|title=1999-00 Modo Hockey Ornskoldsvik [SEL]|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0014322000.html|accessdate=2009-01-20|publisher=Hockeydb}}&lt;/ref&gt; The two brothers played on a [[line (ice hockey)|line]] during the season with [[New York Islanders]] prospect [[Mattias Weinhandl]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Isles' Luongo hoping to stop Milbury's shots|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/2000/01/14/2000-01-14_isles__luongo_hoping_to_stop.html|accessdate=2010-05-17|date=2000-01-14|publisher=''[[New York Daily News]]''|author=Anthony McCarron}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the 2000 playoffs, Daniel added a team-leading eight goals and 14 points.&lt;ref name=modo00/&gt; He recorded two goals and two assists in the deciding game of the semifinals against Brynäs IF, a 6–3 win for Modo.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Brynäs 3 – 6 MODO|url=http://estat.hockeyligan.se/c/LGameStatistics.aspx?LID=142&amp;GameId=24433|accessdate=2010-07-25|publisher=[[Swedish Elite League]]|language=Swedish}}&lt;/ref&gt; Modo made their second straight finals appearance, where they lost the playoff championship to [[Djurgårdens IF Hockey|Djurgårdens IF]] in three straight games.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=SM-slutspel – 1999/2000 (slut)|url=http://estat.hockeyligan.se/c/LStart.aspx?LId=142|accessdate=2011-09-30|publisher=[[Swedish Elite League]]|language=Swedish}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Vancouver Canucks (from 2000)===
====2000–06====
The [[2000–01 NHL season]] was Daniel's first season with the Canucks. His debut was the team's first game of the campaign on October 5, 2000, a 6–3 loss to the [[Philadelphia Flyers]].&lt;ref name=firstgame&gt;{{cite news|title=No Lindros, no problem as Flyers double up on Canucks|url=http://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=KRMOAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=K3oDAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=2913,481918&amp;dq=henrik+sedin&amp;hl=en|accessdate=2010-05-17|date=2000-10-06|publisher=''[[St. Petersburg Times]]''|author=Associated Press}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel and Henrik became the fourth pair of twins to have played in the NHL.&lt;ref name=firstgame/&gt; Three days later, Daniel scored his first career NHL goal against goaltender [[Dan Cloutier]] of the Tampa Bay Lightning.&lt;ref name=firstgoal/&gt; Assisted by Henrik, the goal tied the game at 4–4 with 1:13 minutes left to go in a 5–4 regulation win.&lt;ref name=firstgoal&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks strike Lightning|url=http://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=dUIyAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=GeYFAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=6631,6201724&amp;dq=henrik+sedin&amp;hl=en|accessdate=2010-05-17|date=2000-10-09|publisher=''[[Lawrence Journal-World]]''|author=[[Associated Press]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; On November 30, 2000, he suffered a shoulder injury, sidelining him for four games.&lt;ref name=tsn&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=1911|accessdate=2010-05-17|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; During his recovery, he was reprimanded by Canucks head coach [[Marc Crawford]] who told him that playing through pain is part of being in the NHL.&lt;ref name=slipping&gt;{{Cite news|title=Play of Sedin twins slipping some|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/inside_game/michael_farber/news/2000/12/15/farber_insider/|accessdate=2010-05-17|date=2000-12-15|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''|author=Michael Farber}}&lt;/ref&gt; Later in the season, he missed an additional three games due to a back injury, shortening his rookie season to 75 games.&lt;ref name=tsn/&gt; He became the first rookie in 2000–01 to reach 20 goals when he scored on March 21, 2001, in a 1–1 tie against the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks vs. Blue Jackets|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/scores101/101080/101080333.htm|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2001-03-21|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Finishing the campaign with that goal total, he tied for second among league rookies in scoring with [[Shane Willis]], behind [[Brad Richards]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Player Stats – 2000–2001 – Regular Season – Rookie – All Skaters – Summary – Total Goals|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20012ALLSRSAll&amp;sort=goals&amp;viewName=summary|accessdate=2010-05-28|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He also had 14 assists for 34 points in total.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; Making his [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] debut against the [[Colorado Avalanche]], Daniel recorded an assist in the opening game of the first-round series, a 5–4 loss for the Canucks.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Avalanche 5, Canucks 4|url=http://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=MWMtAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=4ogFAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=5406,2629726&amp;dq=canucks+avalanche&amp;hl=en|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2001-04-13|publisher=''[[The Daily Gazette]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; He added his first NHL playoff goal later in the series as the Canucks were eliminated in four games.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=On Hockey; Penguins Wait for Jagr to Enter the Building|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/26/sports/on-hockey-penguins-wait-for-jagr-to-enter-building.html|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2001-04-26|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|author=Joe Lapointe}}&lt;/ref&gt; He and Henrik played primarily on the Canucks' third line.&lt;ref name=slipping/&gt; Daniel received one third-place vote from the Professional Hockey Writers' Association for the [[Calder Memorial Trophy]] as NHL rookie of the year, finishing eighth in award balloting overall.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|title=The Official 2002 NHL Yearbook|author=National Hockey League|publisher=Faceoff Properties Inc|issn=1481-708X|page=244}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Calder Memorial Trophy|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/page.htm?id=24931|accessdate=2010-08-26|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

During the off-season in May 2001, Daniel underwent surgery for a [[herniated disc]] in his lower back, from which he suffered during the [[2001 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2001 World Championships]] in [[Germany]].&lt;ref name=&quot;back surgery&quot;&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin has disc surgery|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/05/15/sedin010515.html|accessdate=2010-05-17|date=2001-05-15|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; In his [[2001–02 NHL season|second NHL season]], Daniel struggled with the lowest goals total of his career with nine. The campaign included a 25-game stretch without a goal between mid October and the end of November 2001.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Hejduk leads attack against Canucks|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/12/01/canucks011130.html|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2001-12-01|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; With 23 assists, he had 32 points overall.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; Vancouver finished with the eighth [[seed (sports)|seed]] in the [[Western Conference (NHL)|Western Conference]] for the second consecutive year.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Face Off|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/inside_game/kostya_kennedy/news/2002/04/17/kennedy_preview/|accessdate=2010-08-26|date=2002-04-17|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''|author=Kostya Kennedy}}&lt;/ref&gt; Facing the [[Detroit Red Wings]] in the first round, they were eliminated in six games.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=Red Wings bounce Canucks, reach second round|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/cup02/games/2002-04-27-det-van.htm|accessdate=2010-08-26|date=2002-04-27|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''|author=Associated Press}}&lt;/ref&gt; The following season in [[2002–03 NHL season|2002–03]], Daniel continued his point-scoring pace of the previous two campaigns with 14 goals and 17 assists.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; Vancouver finished the regular season fourth overall in the West and advanced to the second round for the first time in Daniel's career. He appeared in a career-high 14 playoff games and recorded six points,&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; as the Canucks were defeated in seven games by the [[Minnesota Wild]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=A Mostly Unfamiliar Four|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/10/sports/hockey-a-mostly-unfamiliar-four.html|accessdate=2010-08-26|date=2003-05-10|publisher=''[[New York Times]]''|author=Joe Lapointe}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel and Henrik were re-signed in the off-season to one-year, [[United States dollar|US$]]1.125 million contracts on July 29, 2003.&lt;ref name=contract03/&gt;

The Sedins began the [[2003–04 NHL season|2003–04 season]] on a line with first-year player [[Jason King (ice hockey)|Jason King]].&lt;ref name=mattress/&gt; The trio were dubbed the &quot;Mattress Line&quot; (two twins and a King) and formed the Canucks' second scoring line until King was re-assigned to the team's minor league affiliate midway through the season.&lt;ref name=mattress&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks rookie breaks through with Sedins|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/canucks/2003-11-10-mattress-line_x.htm|accessdate=2010-05-17|date=2003-11-10|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''|author=Kevin Woodley}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel was awarded his first [[penalty shot (ice hockey)|penalty shot]] on January 17, 2004, in a game against the [[Anaheim Ducks|Mighty Ducks of Anaheim]]. He was stopped by goaltender [[Jean-Sébastien Giguère]] as Anaheim went on to win the game 2–1.&lt;ref name=&quot;canucks alltime&quot;&gt;{{cite web|title=All-Time 07-08|url=http://www.nhl.com/canucks/ext/alltime_07_08.pdf|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]|format=PDF}}&lt;/ref&gt; On February 24, 2004, Daniel recorded his first NHL career [[hat-trick]] with a four-goal effort in a 4–2 win over the Detroit Red Wings.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin pots four as Canucks double up Wings|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2004/02/25/redwings-canucks040224.html|accessdate=2008-11-12|date=2004-02-25|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Company]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Over 82 games, Daniel increased his production to 18 goals and 54 points.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; The Canucks won the [[Northwest Division (NHL)|Northwest Division]] title in the regular season,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Anything goes for Avs|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/cup/2004-04-11-unpredictable-avs_x.htm|accessdate=2010-08-26|date=2004-04-17|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''|author=Theresa Smith}}&lt;/ref&gt; before losing to the [[Calgary Flames]] in the first round of the playoffs.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=New blood|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/hockey/nhl/specials/playoffs/2004/04/22/bc.hkn.lgns.playoffroundup.r/|accessdate=2010-08-26|date=2004-04-22|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel recorded a goal and two assists in the seven-game series.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt;

Daniel was re-signed to a one-year contract on September 10, 2004, during the off-season.&lt;ref name=contract04/&gt; However, due to the [[2004–05 NHL lockout|2004–05 lockout]], Daniel returned to Sweden to play for Modo, along with Henrik and their Canucks teammate [[Markus Näslund]]. He finished [[2004–05 Elitserien season|the season]] with 33 points in 49 games, fourth in team scoring behind [[Peter Forsberg]], Mattias Weinhandl and Henrik.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=2004–05 Modo Hockey [SEL]|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0014322005.html|accessdate=2010-04-18|publisher=Hockeydb}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Daniel Sedin.jpg|thumb|left|Daniel during the [[2005–06 NHL season|2005–06]] season opener.|alt=An ice hockey player leaning over on his bench with his head turned to the right. He wears a dark blue jersey and a visored helmet.]]

When NHL play resumed in [[2005–06 NHL season|2005–06]], Daniel returned to the Canucks and scored 71 points.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; He tied for third in team point-scoring with [[Todd Bertuzzi]], behind Henrik and Näslund.&lt;ref name=canucks06&gt;{{cite web|title=Player Stats – 2005–2006 – Regular season – Vancouver Canucks – All Skaters – Summary – Total Points|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20062VANSASAll&amp;sort=points&amp;viewName=summary|accessdate=2010-04-18|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; His scoring success that season was influenced, in part, by the signing of winger [[Anson Carter]], who played on the Sedins' line and led the team in goal-scoring.&lt;ref name=canucks06/&gt; The trio matched the scoring pace of the Canucks' top line of Näslund, Bertuzzi and [[Brendan Morrison]].&lt;ref name=canucks06/&gt;  Vancouver's head coach at the time, Marc Crawford, recalled that season as marking the Sedins' ascent to leaders on the team, stating that &quot;by the end of that year, they definitely were our top guys. They had surpassed Naslund and Bertuzzi.&quot;&lt;ref name=surprise/&gt; Despite the brothers' individual achievements, the Canucks missed the playoffs for the first time in their careers.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=Canucks to miss playoffs|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/hockey/2002929629_nhl14.html|accessdate=2010-08-26|date=2006-04-14|publisher=''[[Seattle Times]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; During the off-season, Daniel and Henrik re-signed with the Canucks to identical three-year, $10.75&amp;nbsp;million contracts on June 30, 2006.&lt;ref name=contract06/&gt; Despite the Sedins' success with Carter, the Canucks did not re-sign him; he joined the Columbus Blue Jackets the following season.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Blue Jackets sign ex-Canucks Carter to one-year deal|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=2586530|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=2006-09-13|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

====from 2006====
In the [[2006–07 NHL season|2006–07 season]], Daniel established himself as the Canucks' top scorer. He led the team with 36 goals and 84 points to lead the Canucks in scoring.&lt;ref name=cyrus&gt;{{cite news|title=Roberto Luongo Wins Canucks MVP Award|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=451946|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2007-05-04|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He also tied a league record with four goals in overtime over the course of the season.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Rookie can't believe his feat|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/teams/toronto-maple-leafs/story.html?id=c1b7ef9b-109c-4273-9ca9-34338da33ea6|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2008-06-22|publisher=''[[The Edmonton Journal]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel notched his second career NHL hat-trick on February 6, 2007, scoring two goals against goaltender [[Dwayne Roloson]] and one into an empty net.&lt;ref name=&quot;canucks alltime&quot;/&gt; He later took the second penalty shot of his career on March 8, 2007, against the [[Phoenix Coyotes]]. However, he was stopped once again by [[Curtis Joseph]]; Vancouver went on to win the game 4–2.&lt;ref name=&quot;canucks alltime&quot;/&gt;  Winger [[Taylor Pyatt]], acquired in a trade from the [[Buffalo Sabres]] during the off-season, replaced Carter as the Sedins' linemate&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Pyatt doing just fine bulging the twine|url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=e8aa91f8-bb0d-4ab3-99a2-93cbde21eaff|accessdate=2010-03-15|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''|date=2006-10-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; and went on to score a career-high 23&amp;nbsp;goals. In the opening game of the [[2007 Stanley Cup playoffs|2007 playoffs]] against the [[Dallas Stars]], Daniel assisted on Henrik's quadruple-[[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal to end the longest-ever Canucks playoff game and the sixth longest in NHL history at 138 minutes and six seconds of play.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Marathon win in a whale of a wakeup call|url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=86a6c620-a3a0-402b-9d0e-1d7fb509906f|accessdate=2009-01-20|date=2007-04-12|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel struggled to produce offensively in the playoffs, however, managing five points over 12 games as the Canucks were eliminated by the Anaheim Ducks in the second round.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=Ducks knock out Canucks in double OT|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2007/05/04/nhl-canucks-ducks.html|accessdate=2010-05-04|date=2007-05-04|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Image:Sedins 12-2007.jpg|thumb|right|Daniel (front) and Henrik (back) line up for a faceoff during a game in December 2007.|alt=Two twin ice hockey players in ready positions on the ice, lining up for a faceoff. One player in the forefront, is leaning forwards, putting his weight on his stick on the ice, while the other player in the background is standing upright. They are both looking intently forward. They wear blue jerseys with white trim and blue visored helmets.]]
Daniel recorded 74 points in [[2007–08 NHL season|2007–08]],&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; as the Canucks missed the playoffs for the second time in three years. He finished second in team point-scoring to Henrik and first in goals with 29.&lt;ref name=canucks08&gt;{{cite web|title=Player Stats – 2007–08 – Regular Season – Vancouver Canucks – All Skaters – Summary|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20082VANSASAll&amp;sort=points&amp;viewName=summary|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Sedins saw some time with Näslund on their top line during the season to form an all-Swedish forward unit.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Naslund, Sedin twins keep points coming for Canucks|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=370574|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2008-02-14|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]|author=Karl Samuelson}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Naslund may be moved off Sedins' line|url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=83fffc58-9244-4db3-98c6-cd09f9173db9|date=2008-01-05|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[2008–09 NHL season|following season]], Daniel recorded 31 goals and 82 points, tying Henrik for the team lead in points.&lt;ref name=cyrus2&gt;{{cite web|title=Player Stats – 2008–2009 – Regular Season – Vancouver Canucks – All Skaters – Summary|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20092VANSASAll&amp;sort=points&amp;viewName=summary|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He opened the campaign being named the NHL's [[Three stars (ice hockey)|First Star of the Week]] on October 13, 2008, with a five-point effort over two games.&lt;ref name=&quot;first star&quot;&gt;{{Cite news|title=Daniel Sedin picked NHL's 1st star of the week|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2008/10/13/nhl-three-stars.html|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2008-10-13|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Steve Bernier]] had been acquired in the 2008 off-season in another trade with the Sabres, and began the season on the top line with the Sedins.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title='Average' twins under scrutiny|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/teams/vancouver-canucks/story.html?id=3a17550f-6950-4a89-820b-73448a7b961b&amp;add_feed_url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.canada.com%2Ftheprovince%2Fnews%2Fsports%2Fcanucks%2Ftopstories.atom%3Fviewer%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.faceoff.com%2Fhockey%2Fteams%2Fvancouver-canucks%2Fstory.html|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=2008-10-19|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Bernier was later removed;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Sedin twins get new linemate|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2008/10/30/canucks-kings.html|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=2008-10-30|publisher=[[CBC Sports]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; on February 12, 2009, head coach [[Alain Vigneault]] moved [[Alexandre Burrows]] up from the third line during a game against the Phoenix Coyotes.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Burrows earns promotion|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/teams/vancouver-canucks/story.html?id=1287412&amp;add_feed_url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.faceoff.com%2Fscripts%2FSP6Atom.aspx%3Fid%3D830270|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=2009-02-13|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''|author=Brad Ziemer}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; Late in the campaign, Daniel was named the NHL's Second Star of the Week on March 30, 2009, after recording four goals and four assists in four games, including a game-winning goal.&lt;ref name=&quot;second star&quot;&gt;{{Cite web|title=Mason, Sedin, Ward earn NHL weekly honours|url=http://www.faceoff.com/story.html?id=9e62af39-0125-423b-9318-f998fcf3dcd0|accessdate=2010-08-19|date=2009-03-30|publisher=CanWest News Service}}&lt;/ref&gt; He added 10 points over 10 games in the [[2009 Stanley Cup playoffs|2009 playoffs]],&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; helping the Canucks advance to the second round, where they were defeated in six games by the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Hawks win a wild one, advance to West final|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2008030246|accessdate=2010-04-19|date=2009-05-11|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Set to become unrestricted free agents on July 1, 2009, Daniel and Henrik began negotiating with the Canucks in the off-season and were reported to have asked for 12-year, $63 million contracts in mid-June.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=487017&amp;navid=DL|NHL|Home|title=Gillis made signing Sedins a priority; Luongo next|accessdate=2010-08-19|date=2009-08-29|publisher=National Hockey League|author=Todd Kimberley}}&lt;/ref&gt; With free agency looming, Canucks general manager [[Mike Gillis]] visited the Sedins in Sweden, where they agreed on identical five-year, $30.5 million contracts on July 1.&lt;ref name=contract09&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks commit $61M to Sedins|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2009/07/01/sp-hockey-sedins-staying.html|accessdate=2009-09-04|date=2009-07-01|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Four games into the [[2009–10 NHL season|2009–10 season]], Daniel suffered the first major injury of his career, breaking his foot in a game against the [[Montreal Canadiens]]. He suffered the injury after being hit by a slapshot from teammate [[Alex Edler]].  Although Daniel finished the game and recorded three assists, x-rays several days later revealed a fracture.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Canucks' Daniel Sedin out 4–6 weeks with broken foot|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=294545|accessdate=2009-10-11|date=2009-10-11|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He was sidelined for 18 games, returning to the ice on November 22 against the Chicago Blackhawks.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=Signs point to Sedin for hot Hawks|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2009/11/22/sp-chi-van.html|accessdate=2009-11-22|date=2009-11-22|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Soon after his return, he notched his third career NHL hat-trick in a 4–2 win against the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] on December 10.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Daniel Sedin scores hat trick as Canucks down Thrashers. |url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=301894|accessdate=2009-12-11|date=2009-12-10|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Four days later, he was named the NHL's Second Star of the Week with seven points over the course of the week.&lt;ref name=&quot;second star2&quot;&gt;{{cite news|title=Quick grabs NHL's first star|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2009/12/14/sp-nhl-stars.html|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2009-12-14|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the final game of the regular season, on April 10, 2010, against the Calgary Flames, Daniel scored his fourth career NHL hat-trick in a 7–3 win. All three goals were assisted by his brother, helping Henrik pass [[Alexander Ovechkin]] for the [[Art Ross Trophy]] as the league's leading point-scorer.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=All hail Henrik Sedin|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/hockey/2010/04/11/13542076.html|accessdate=2010-04-11|date=2010-04-11|publisher=''[[Toronto Sun]]''|author=Hosea Chung}}&lt;/ref&gt; The last goal was chosen by [[The Sports Network]] in a fan-voted poll as the NHL's play of the year; Daniel received a between-the-legs tip pass from Henrik near the corner boards before beating goaltender [[Miika Kiprusoff]] with a between-the-legs deke.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=No doubt about it; Sedin wins play of the year showdown|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/special/?id=25182|accessdate=2010-05-31|date=2010-05-31|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel finished the season with a career-high 56 assists and 85 points despite playing an injury-shortened 63-game campaign.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; His 1.35 points per game rate was third in the league behind Henrik and Ovechkin.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=2009–2010 Regular Season – All Skaters – Points – Average Points Per Game|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20102ALLSASAll&amp;sort=avgPointsPerGame&amp;viewName=points|accessdate=2010-05-17|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the subsequent [[2010 Stanley Cup playoffs|2010 playoffs]], Daniel recorded 10 points in the opening round against the [[Los Angeles Kings]], including the series-winning goal in the late stages of game six.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Stars are the difference for Canucks|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs/2010/columns/story?columnist=lebrun_pierre&amp;id=5136029|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2010-04-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Pierre LeBrun}}&lt;/ref&gt; Against the Chicago Blackhawks the following round, his production decreased to four points as the Canucks were eliminated in six games.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Blackhawks put away Canucks|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/stanleycup/story/2010/05/11/sp-nhl-blackhawks-canucks-game-6.html|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2010-05-11|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the off-season, Daniel was named to the [[NHL All-Star Team|NHL Second All-Star Team]].&lt;ref name=&quot;second allstar&quot;&gt;{{cite news|title=Henrik Sedin and Daniel Sedin named to NHL's first and second all-star teams|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=532558|accessdate=2010-08-22|date=2010-06-23|publisher=National Hockey League}}&lt;/ref&gt; It marked the first time since [[1973–74 NHL season|1973–74]] that two brothers were named post-season NHL All-Stars, as Henrik had been named to the First Team.&lt;ref name=&quot;second allstar&quot;/&gt; They were also chosen to appear together on the cover of [[EA Sports]]' European version of the ''[[NHL 11]]'' video game.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Can Vancouver Canucks Henrik Sedin rack up another triple-digit season?|url=http://www.straight.com/article-344856/vancouver/can-vancouver-canuck-henrik-sedin-rack-another-tripledigit-season|accessdate=2010-09-09|publisher=''[[Georgia Straight]]''|author=Jeff Paterson|date=2010-09-07}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On October 9, 2010, Daniel was named an alternate captain for the Canucks, who named Henrik captain during a pre-game ceremony to celebrate the team's 40th anniversary.&lt;ref name=alternate/&gt; He was joined by [[Ryan Kesler]], [[Kevin Bieksa]] and [[Manny Malhotra]] as alternates. Daniel wears the &quot;A&quot; during Canucks home games, along with Kesler.&lt;ref name=alternate&gt;{{cite news|title=Henrik Sedin named captain|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=336908|accessdate=2010-10-10|date=2010-10-09|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; On January 10, 2011, he was named the NHL's First Star of the Week after scoring five goals and seven points in four games.&lt;ref name=&quot;first star2&quot;&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin named NHL's 1st star of week|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2011/01/10/sp-daniel-sedin-nhl-first-star.html|accessdate=2011-01-12|date=2011-01-10|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; During that span, he scored the 10,000th goal in Canucks franchise history in a 3–1 win against the Flames on January 5.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=The Goods: Canucks Keep Rolling|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=548523|accessdate=2011-01-05|date=2010-05-01|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Later in the month, Daniel competed in his first career [[2011 NHL All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]. Drafted onto Team [[Eric Staal|Staal]], he played with Canucks teammate [[Ryan Kesler]] opposite Henrik on Team [[Nicklas Lidstrom|Lidstrom]]. In the Skills Competition, Daniel won the shooting accuracy segment by first beating [[Martin Havlat]] to all four targets in 7.3 seconds, then defeating [[Patrick Kane]] in the final in 8.9 seconds.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=2011 Honda NHL SuperSkills results|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/page.htm?id=67469|accessdate=2011-05-22|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; The following day, Daniel recorded one assist as Team Staal lost the game 11–10.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Game Boxscore|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/boxscore.htm?id=2010040058|accessdate=2011-05-22|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Towards the end of the 2010–11 season, Daniel compiled three goals and five assists in three games to be named the NHL's Second Star of the Week on March 14, 2011.&lt;ref name=&quot;second star3&quot;/&gt; During that month, he totalled 9 goals and 12 assists in 15 games, earning him NHL Second Star of the Month honours.&lt;ref name=&quot;march 2011&quot;/&gt; With a goal and an assist against the Los Angeles Kings on March 31,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks beat Kings to win Presidents' Trophy for first time|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=360323|accessdate=2011-04-01|date=2011-03-31|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel became the fifth player in team history to reach the [[List of NHL players with 100-point seasons|100-point mark]] in one season (after [[Pavel Bure]], [[Alexander Mogilny]], Markus Naslund and Henrik Sedin).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Regular Season - Vancouver Canucks - All Skaters - Single Season Leaders For Team - Career Points|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/careerstats.htm?fetchKey=00002VANSAHAll&amp;sort=points&amp;viewName=careerLeadersSingleSeasonForTeam|accessdate=2011-03-31|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Image:Sedins Art Ross plaques.JPG|thumb|left|Daniel's plaque (right) on the Art Ross Trophy, beside Henrik's (left).]]
Prior to the Canucks' final home game of the season a week later, he was awarded the [[Cyclone Taylor Award]] as the team's most valuable player (MVP) and his third Cyrus H. McLean Award as the team's leading point-scorer.&lt;ref name=canucksawards11/&gt; Finishing the campaign with a career-high 41 goals, 63 assists and 104 points, he won the [[Art Ross Trophy]] as the league's leading point-scorer. It marked the first time in NHL history that brothers led the league in scoring in back-to-back seasons, as Henrik had won the previous year. Chicago Blackhawks forwards [[Doug Bentley|Doug]] and [[Max Bentley]] also won separate scoring titles, but had achieved the feat three years apart in 1943 and 1946, respectively.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin wins Art Ross|url=http://www.iihf.com/sk/home-of-hockey/news/news-singleview/article/daniel-sedin-wins-art-ross.html?tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=247&amp;cHash=3d59b62dad|accessdate=2011-04-28|date=2011-04-11|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He also received the [[Viking Award]] as the league's best Swedish player, following after Henrik who received it the year before.{{#tag:ref|The award is voted on by all Swedish players in the NHL.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin får Viking Award|url=http://www.modohockey.se/nyheter.cfm?nyhet=6028|accessdate=2011-06-14|date=2011-06-11|publisher=[[Modo Hockey]]}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;}}

Daniel's efforts helped the Canucks win the [[Presidents' Trophy]] as the team with the league's best regular season record for the first in franchise history. Entering the [[2011 Stanley Cup playoffs|2011 playoffs]] with the top seed in the West, the Canucks beat the Chicago Blackhawks, [[Nashville Predators]] and [[San Jose Sharks]] in the first three rounds to advance to the [[2011 Stanley Cup Finals|Stanley Cup Finals]] for the first time in 17 years. Playing against the [[Boston Bruins]], the Sedins struggled to score in the Finals; through the series' seven games, Daniel recorded a goal and three assists. Consequently, the Canucks managed just eight goals in that same span. After losing Game 6 by a 5–2 score in Boston, Daniel told ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'' reporters, &quot;We're going to win Game 7.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin: We'll win Game 7|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/nhl/news/story?id=6659965|accessdate=2011-06-14|date=2011-06-14|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=LeBrun, Pierre|agency=Associted Press}}&lt;/ref&gt; They went on to lose the deciding contest 4–0.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Bruins win Cup by blanking Canucks 4–0|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2010030417|accessdate=2011-06-24|date=2011-06-16|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]|author=Rosen, Dan}}&lt;/ref&gt; With 9 goals and 20 points over 25 games, Daniel ranked fourth in playoff scoring behind Boston's [[David Krejci]], Henrik Sedin and Tampa Bay's [[Martin St. Louis]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=2010-2011 - Players - All Skaters - Points - Total Points|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20113ALLSASAll&amp;sort=points&amp;viewName=summary|accessdate=2011-06-24|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; His 99 shots on goal marked the fifth-highest single playoffs total in NHL history.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Playoffs - Skater - Single-Season Leaders - All Teams - Shots|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/careerstats.htm?fetchKey=00003ALLSAHALL&amp;sort=shots&amp;viewName=careerLeadersSingleSeason|accessdate=2011-12-25|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

A week after the Canucks' loss, Daniel was in attendance for the NHL Awards show in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], having been nominated for the [[Hart Memorial Trophy]] as the league's most valuable player, the [[Ted Lindsay Award]] as the league's most outstanding player and the [[NHL Foundation Player Award]] for he and Henrik's work in the Vancouver community. Daniel won the Lindsay Award over forwards Martin St. Louis of the Tampa Bay Lightning and [[Corey Perry]] of the Anaheim Ducks. In Hart Trophy voting, he finished as the first runner-up to Perry with 51 first-place ballots and 960 voting points total (16 and 83 fewer than Perry, respectively). Daniel and Henrik also lost the NHL Foundation Award to Los Angeles Kings captain [[Dustin Brown (ice hockey)|Dustin Brown]]. After being named to the NHL's Second All-Star Team the previous year, Daniel received First Team honours with Henrik for the 2010–11 season.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks' Daniel Sedin wins Ted Lindsay Award as NHL players' MVP, but comes up short on Hart|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Canucks+Daniel+Sedin+wins+Lindsay+Award+players+comes+short+Hart/4989920/story.html|accessdate=2011-06-24|date=2011-06-23|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|author=Ziemer, Brad|publisher=Postmedia News}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; Returning to Sweden in the off-season, Daniel and Henrik were co-recipients of the [[Victoria Stipendium]], as the country's athletes of the year. They became the third and fourth ice hockey players to receive the award, after [[Stefan Persson (ice hockey)|Stefan Persson]] in 1980 and [[Peter Forsberg]] in 1994. Henrik and Daniel were presented the award, commemorated with glass plates, on July 14, 2011, in the city of [[Borgholm]].&lt;ref name=stipendium&gt;{{cite news|title=The Victoria Stipendium|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=569608|accessdate=2011-08-27|date=2011-07-18|publisher=[[Vancouver Canucks]]|author=Jory, Derek}}&lt;/ref&gt;

At the midway point the following season, Daniel was named to his second consecutive [[2012 NHL All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game in January 2012]]. He was one of four players representing the Canucks, including Henrik, [[Alex Edler]] and [[Cody Hodgson]].{{#tag:ref|Hodgson was named as one of 12 designated rookies who participated in the skills competition, but not the game.|group=notes}}&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Sedins, Edler, Hodgson earn stars|url=http://www.theprovince.com/sports/Sedins+Edler+Hodgson+earn+stars/5990303/story.html|accessdate=2012-01-14|date=2012-01-13|work=[[The Province]]|author=Kuzma, Ben|publisher=Postmedia News|location=Vancouver}}&lt;/ref&gt; Chosen to Team [[Daniel Alfredsson|Alfredsson]] in the All-Star Draft, he recorded a goal and an assist in a 12–9 loss to Team [[Zdeno Chara|Chara]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=2012 NHL All-Star Game Boxscore|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/boxscore.htm?id=2011040059|accessdate=2012-04-04|publisher=National Hockey League}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Later in the season, Daniel sustained a concussion after receiving a hit from Blackhawks defenceman [[Duncan Keith]] during a game on March 21, 2012. With Daniel in the neutral zone and without possession of the puck, Keith hit him in the head with his elbow. After being helped off the ice by a trainer, Daniel remained in the game for a shift before leaving the contest entirely. Two days later, Keith was suspended five games for his hit by the league.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Duncan Keith suspended 5 games for elbowing Daniel Sedin|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/story/2012/03/23/sp-hockey-chicago-blackhawks-vancouver-canucks-concussion-daniel-sedin.html|accessdate=2012-04-04|date=2012-03-23|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|agency=Canadian Press}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==International play==
