{{MedalCompetition | [[World U17 Hockey Challenge]]}}
{{MedalSilver | 1997 Canada |}}
{{MedalBottom}}

Daniel made his North American debut competing for Sweden in the 1997 [[World U17 Hockey Challenge]], held in [[Alberta]]. Leading the tournament in scoring with 26 points (9 goals and 17 assists) over 6 games, he helped Sweden to a silver medal. After going undefeated in five contests, they were defeated in the gold medal game by Team [[Ontario]] 6–2.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|title=Before they were stars: 25 years of great performances at the World U17 Hockey Challenge|url=http://www.hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/156190/la_id/1/|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2011-01-01|publisher=[[Hockey Canada]]|author=Derek Jory}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Back in Europe, Daniel competed at the 1997 European Junior Championships, recording two goals and six points over six games. The following year, at the 1998 European Junior Championships, Sweden's final game required them to beat Russia by four goals to surpass Finland in [[goal difference|goal differential]] and win the gold medal. Daniel recorded two assists as Sweden won 5–1.&lt;ref name=mirror/&gt;

In his NHL draft year, Daniel competed for Sweden at the [[1999 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|1999 World Junior Championships]] in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]].  He recorded 10 points in six games, and tied for second in tournament scoring with [[Daniel Tkaczuk]] of [[Canada national junior hockey team|Canada]] and [[Scott Gomez]] of the [[USA Hockey|United States]], behind [[Brian Gionta]] of the United States.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Final Scoring|url=http://hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/2101/la_id/1.htm|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=[[Hockey Canada]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Sweden failed to medal, losing the bronze medal game against Slovakia by a 5–4 score.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=World Jr. Championship results/schedule|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/wjc99/sked.htm#result|accessdate=2010-05-30|1999-01-06|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Later that year, Daniel made his debut for the [[Sweden national men's ice hockey team|Swedish men's team]] at the [[1999 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1999 World Championships]] in [[Norway]]. He notched one assist over nine games as Sweden won the bronze medal.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Schedule/Results|url=http://hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/22056/la_id/1.htm|accessdate=2010-05-04|publisher=[[Hockey Canada]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2000, Daniel once again competed in both the [[2000 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|World Junior]] and [[2000 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|Men's Championships]]. At the junior tournament in Sweden, Daniel matched his previous year's output with 10 points. He was the third highest point-scorer in the tournament, behind Henrik and [[Milan Kraft]] of the Czech Republic.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Scoring leaders|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/9900/U20a/gs/pg000007.htm|accessdate=2010-04-18|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Again, Sweden failed to earn a medal, finishing in fifth place.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=IIHF Championships 2000|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/9900/U20a/9900/htm/u20a_fr.htm|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; At the Men's World Championships, Daniel and Henrik both recorded five points; they were the youngest players on the squad.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Team Sweden|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/9900/wsa00/cs/pg000083.htm|accessdate=2010-06-01|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Sweden did not achieve a medal, losing to [[Finland national men's ice hockey team|Finland]] in the quarterfinal.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Final Round|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/9900/wsa00/cs/pg000027.htm|accessdate=2010-05-30|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Image:Sedins faceoff 2010 oly.jpg|thumb|left|Daniel (No. 22) receives a faceoff win from brother Henrik (No. 20) against [[Slovakia national men's ice hockey team|Slovak]] forward [[Michal Handzus]].|alt=A faceoff during an ice hockey game. The player at the top left has directed the puck to his teammate next to him as his opponent, bent over, looks on.]]
Following his rookie season with the Vancouver Canucks, Daniel made his third World Championships appearance, in [[2001 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2001]] in [[Germany]]. He was injured midway through the tournament and had to return to Vancouver for surgery on a [[herniated disc]] in his lower back.&lt;ref name=&quot;back surgery&quot;/&gt; Sweden defeated the [[United States national men's ice hockey team|United States]] 3–2 to win its second bronze medal in three years.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Playoff Round|url=http://www.iihf.com/hockey/x/0001/WS/cs/pg000010.htm|accessdate=2010-05-04|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He made a fourth tournament appearance at the [[2005 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|2005 World Championships]] in [[Austria]]. Sweden missed out on the bronze medal, losing to [[Russia national men's ice hockey team|Russia]] 6–3.&lt;ref name=&quot;sweden russia&quot;/&gt; Daniel had an assist in a losing effort during the bronze medal game.&lt;ref name=&quot;sweden russia&quot;&gt;{{cite web|title=Game Summary|url=http://www.iihf.com/Hydra/Tournaments_05/output/ws/hydra.iihf.com/data/iihf/output/xml/1000000009/IHM1000000009155_74_1_0.html|accessdate=2010-05-04|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He finished with nine points in nine games, which tied for fourth in tournament-scoring.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Scoring Leaders|url=http://www.iihf.com/Hydra/Tournaments_05/output/ws/hydra.iihf.com/data/iihf/output/xml/1000000009/IHM1000000009Z39_85B_1_0.html|accessdate=2010-06-01|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On December 22, 2005, Daniel was named to the Swedish Olympic team for the [[Ice hockey at the Winter Olympics|2006 Winter Games]] in [[Turin]], Italy.&lt;ref name=2006oly&gt;{{cite news|title=Swedish hockey roster stacked for Torino|url=http://www.cbc.ca/olympics/story/2005/12/22/sweden-hockey051222.html|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2005-12-22|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; He joined Henrik, Markus Näslund and [[Mattias Öhlund]] as one of four Canucks on the squad.&lt;ref name=2006oly/&gt; Competing in his first Olympics, he contributed four points as Sweden won a gold medal,&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt; defeating Finland 3–2 in the final.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=FIN – SWE 2–3|url=http://www.iihf.com/Hydra/OG06/data/iihf/output/xml/11/IHM400101_74_3_0.pdf|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2006-02-26|publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]]|format=PDF}}&lt;/ref&gt; Four years later, he was once again named to the Swedish Olympic team for the [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics - Men's tournament|2010 Winter Games]] in [[Vancouver]].&lt;ref name=10oly&gt;{{cite news|title=Team Sweden names 2010 Olympic roster|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=511196|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2009-12-27|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]|author=Shawn P. Roarke}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Despite going into the tournament as one of Sweden's key players (in the corresponding NHL season, he was third among Swedish players in points despite missing 19 games),&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=2009–2010 – Regular Season – All Skaters – SWE – Summary|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20102ALLSASSWE&amp;sort=points&amp;viewName=summary|accessdate=2010-06-01|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; he ranked seventh among team forwards in total ice time.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Team Sweden tournament standings and statistics|url=http://www.vancouver2010.com/olympic-hockey/schedule-and-results/men_ihm400000nSWE-vtour_team_stats-RP.html|accessdate=2010-06-01|publisher=[[Vancouver Organizing Committee for the 2010 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games|Vancouver Organizing Committee]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; Sweden failed to defend their gold medal from Turin, losing to [[Slovakia national men's ice hockey team|Slovakia]] in the quarterfinal.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Slovakia upsets Sweden 4–3 in quarterfinals to send defending champions packing|url=http://www.thehockeynews.com/articles/31740-Slovakia-upsets-Sweden-43-in-quarterfinals-to-send-defending-champs-packing.html|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2010-02-25|publisher=''[[The Hockey News]]''|author=Josh Ferguson}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel had a goal and two assists in four games.&lt;ref name=nhl/&gt;

==Playing style==
[[Image:Sedins 04-2010.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Daniel (centre left) completes a pass to Henrik (right), while being checked by [[Los Angeles Kings]] defenceman [[Matt Greene]] during the [[2010 Stanley Cup playoffs|2010 playoffs]].|alt=Two ice hockey teammates in the process of passing to one another, while an opposing player checks one of them into the boards. The teammates are dressed in a blue jersey, while the opposing player is dressed in white.]]
Throughout his career, Daniel has been known as a goal-scorer, usually finishing plays initiated by his brother, Henrik.&lt;ref name=surprise/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;have hart&quot;/&gt; However, Daniel is also a proficient [[wiktionary:playmaker|playmaker]] and generates many sequences with Henrik off the [[wiktionary:cycle|cycle]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Kessel responds to spotlight, Henrik Sedin shines in shadows|url=http://m.si.com/news/wr/wr/detail/2126123;jsessionid=CDEEA7CD3D50114FD5326CE8ECE4B311.cnnsi1|accessdate=2010-08-19|date=2009-12-16|publisher=''[[Sports Illustrated]]''|author=Darren Eliot}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Bernier does a lot of things well, but Sedins need more|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/nhlnews/story.html?id=af66ce00-1098-4728-8f67-61cef79b5022|accessdate=2010-04-19|date=2008-10-29|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Daniel's familiarity with Henrik's play enhances his effectiveness; the pair are known for their ability to find each other intuitively with passes,&lt;ref name=surprise&gt;{{cite news|title=Surprised by Sedin? You shouldn't be|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/story?columnist=lebrun_pierre&amp;id=4883674|accessdate=2010-04-19|date=2010-02-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Pierre LeBrun}}&lt;/ref&gt; often without looking.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Can they be this good? Pinch us!|url=http://www.canada.com/sports/they+this+good/2684108/story.html|accessdate=2010-04-19|date=2010-03-15|publisher=''[[The Province]]''|author=Jason Botchford}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=NHL One-Timer: Twin trouble|url=http://www.covers.com/articles/articles.aspx?theArt=132805&amp;t=0|accessdate=2010-04-19|publisher=Covers|author=Andrew Folkes}}&lt;/ref&gt;

With offensive skill marking the prime component of his game, Daniel is known to avoid initiating contact with opposing players.  Early in their career, he and Henrik were knocked off the puck easily, leading many in the media to refer to them as the &quot;Sedin Sisters&quot;.&lt;ref name=surprise/&gt;  As a result, players have often taken advantage of their lack of physicality by playing aggressively against them.  This once led Canucks general manager Brian Burke to publicly complain, commenting during a [[2002 Stanley Cup playoffs|2002 playoff]] series against the Detroit Red Wings, &quot;'Sedin' is not Swedish for 'punch me or headlock me in a scrum'.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Top Canucks prospect Cody Hodgson to return to game action|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/teams/story.html?id=2510345&amp;add_feed_url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.faceoff.com%2Fscripts%2FSP6Atom.aspx%3Fid%3D830270|accessdate=2010-04-19|date=2010-02-01|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''|author=Elliott Papp}}&lt;/ref&gt;  As their careers progressed, the Sedins have worked on their strength, improving their puck possession, allowing them to play more effectively.&lt;ref name=surprise/&gt;

==Personal life==
Daniel met his wife Marinette in his hometown Örnsköldsvik, Sweden, around 1998.&lt;ref name=vancouversun/&gt; She came with him to Vancouver upon the start of Daniel's NHL career in 2000,&lt;ref name=reader&gt;{{cite news|title=The Sedins raise their own reader|url=http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/story.html?id=0644bb92-078a-4dcb-ab36-5f88e62d2d7b%20|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2007-10-02|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the two married in 2005.&lt;ref name=vancouversun/&gt; After earning a bachelor's degree in psychology at the [[University of British Columbia]]&lt;ref name=reader/&gt; Marinette became involved with the Canucks Family Education Centre, helping female immigrants transition to the English language.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Daniel Sedin's better half is hleping others make the transition into a new world|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=499514|accessdate=2010-05-30|date=2009-09-23|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]|author=Derek Jory}}&lt;/ref&gt; Together, they have two daughters, Ronja (born in 2006) and Anna (born in March 2011), and a son, Erik (born in 2008).&lt;ref name=vancouversun/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Manny Malhotra's injury hits team hard|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Manny+Malhotra+injury+hits+team+hard/4488361/story.html|accessdate=2011-03-23|date=2011-03-23|work=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|publisher=Postmedia News|location=Vancouver}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt; They live in the Vancouver neighbourhood of [[Shaughnessy, Vancouver|Shaughnessy]] during the NHL season, returning to Sweden every summer.&lt;ref name=vancouversun&gt;{{cite web|title=Daniel Sedin|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/Daniel+Sedin/2923316/story.html|accessdate=2010-08-19|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''|author=Yvonne Zacharias|date=2010-04-19}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In March 2010, Daniel and Marinette made a joint $1.5 million donation with Henrik and his wife Johanna to the [[BC Children's Hospital]]'s $200-million project for a new building. The two families requested that it be put towards a [[pediatric intensive-care unit]] and a [[diagnostic imaging]] area.&lt;ref name=donation&gt;{{cite news|title=Canucks' Sedin twins make $1.5-million donation to BC Children's Hospital project|url=http://www.globaltvbc.com/canucks+sedin+twins+make+15-million+donation+to+bc+childrens+hospital+project/72512/story.html|accessdate=2010-03-11|date=2010-03-11|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''|author=Darah Hansen}}&lt;/ref&gt;

